Business Day

Private Sector; A Cool Head for 4th and Long

By DONNA ROSATOFEB. 9, 2003



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









WHEN Joseph H. Moglia landed his first job on Wall Street 19 years ago, he was 34, the father of four young children and the only sales trainee in his group at Merrill Lynch without an M.B.A.A former college football coach, Mr. Moglia became the No. 1 institutional sales representative in his fourth year at Merrill. Later, he became the youngest senior vice president and the head of all investment products in the private-client division. He said he had expected to stay at the firm until he retired.But when he was chosen as the chief executive of a struggling online trading firm, Ameritrade Holding, during one of the worst stock market slumps in decades, he said he could not pass up the challenge.''Had things not been as bad as they were, they might not have been interested in me; I felt that this was an incredible challenge,'' said Mr. Moglia, who took over as chief from Ameritrade's founder and chairman, J. Joe Ricketts, in March 2001.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Moglia had built a reputation as a turnaround specialist, both as a coach and as a businessman, but he had his work cut out for him at Ameritrade, a money-losing venture that many analysts predicted would not survive. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Now, nearly two years into the job, Mr. Moglia, at 53, is praised for turning around Ameritrade while rival online brokers, like the E*Trade Group, are floundering. ''The company has responded extremely well to Joe Moglia's leadership,'' said Richard H. Repetto, an analyst at Putnam Lovell NBF Securities.Unlike E*Trade, which diversified into banking, Ameritrade has remained an online brokerage firm. Mr. Moglia's strategy has been to add heft by acquiring rivals, paying $154 million in stock for National Discount Brokers in September 2001, for example, and $1.3 billion in stock for Datek Online last September.At the same time, he reduced costs and cut the company's bank debt nearly to zero. Even if the average number of daily trades fell by one-third, Ameritrade would still break even, Mr. Moglia said.The company, which lost $29 million on sales of $431 million in the fiscal year ended last September, is projecting a profit for fiscal 2003 -- its first full-year profit since 1999. For the last quarter, Ameritrade had net income of $22 million, a record, on sales of $181 million.Charles Schwab, by contrast, lost $79 million in the fourth quarter on sales of $996 million. E*Trade earned $30 million on sales of $349 million, but it warned that this quarter's operating earnings would be 20 percent below the fourth quarter's.Though Schwab has $765 billion in customer accounts -- 20 times Ameritrade's $37 billion -- Ameritrade is adding accounts faster. In the last two years, its account base grew 30 percent, not including acquisitions, compared with 6 percent for Schwab and 15 percent for E*Trade, according to Putnam Lovell.Mr. Moglia is not afraid to play rough with competitors. Ameritrade announced in full-page national newspaper ads on Thursday that it would pay up to $50 to each investor willing to switch at least $10,000 to an Ameritrade account.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

But even supporters say Ameritrade and other online brokerage firms are facing a tough contest in a weak economy. ''Joe's challenge will be the viability of the online business model and not his ability to run the business,'' said David H. Komansky, the chairman of Merrill Lynch.
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


