Mr. Moglia said he thrived on such challenges. When he was at Merrill, for example, Mr. Komansky, then the head of institutional sales, asked him to take over the municipal bond division after Orange County, Calif., filed the largest municipal bankruptcy ever. The county had lost billions on risky investments recommended by Merrill. When Mr. Moglia left three years later, the division was generating more profit per employee than any other in the firm.''Joe is fearless,'' Mr. Komansky said. ''He went into a very different business and in short order became proficient at it and really turned around and energized the unit. A lot of people can accept new assignments within their range of experience, but far fewer people can go outside their expertise and excel like that.''Mr. Moglia, the oldest of five children, grew up in a two-bedroom, one-bathroom apartment in Washington Heights in Manhattan. His mother was a homemaker until her children were adults, and his father owned a fruit store in the neighborhood.''Watching how hard my father worked gave me an incredible sense of responsibility but also taught me how important it was for me to finish school and do something I enjoyed,'' Mr. Moglia said. He said he had worked long hours at the fruit store throughout high school, at Fordham Prep, and then in college, at Fordham University in the Bronx, where he earned a degree in economics.A football and baseball player in high school, he switched to coaching at college because he was married and a father by the time he was 19. While he was still a sophomore at Fordham University, he persuaded Fordham Prep to hire him as an assistant football coach.Though his interest in Wall Street grew while studying economics in college, Mr. Moglia truly enjoyed coaching. After graduation, he applied to more than 100 high schools and was offered a head coaching position at only one, Archmere Academy, a boys' prep school in Delaware where the football team had won only three games in the previous three years. In his final season, four years later, Archmere had a record of 8-1.Mr. Moglia eventually moved on to college football at Lafayette and then Dartmouth, as defensive coordinator, where his team won Ivy League championships in 1981 and 1982. But the 90-hour workweeks and travel were too taxing. ''I loved what I was doing, and I was good at it,'' he said. ''But after 15 years' coaching, I wondered if the sacrifice I and my family were making was worth it.''He applied for the Merrill training program and quickly worked his way up at the firm.Mr. Moglia married Amy Jardine, an artist, eight years ago and has two teenage stepsons, and he is close to his four adult children from his first marriage.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

He said he saw many parallels in coaching and running a business. Maintaining communication and building a strong team are vital to success in both, he said. To that end, he meets with Ameritrade's 2,000 employees every few weeks.His message: ''We know that one day there's going to be a good market, but we'll be even tougher on ourselves then. We're going to be the best there is.''Tom Olivadotti, the linebacker coach for the New York Giants, has known Mr. Moglia since both coached high school teams and said: ''You have to be a team builder and motivate people to win. Joe does that.'' Continue reading the main story






